Headlines.Headline: Correction to Wisconsin Energy Story

PARAGRAPH.#text: "Wisconsin Energy to Buy Integrys for $5.71 Billion," published at 7:49 a.m. EDT, incorrectly described the constitution of the per-share price. Rather, Integrys shareholders will receive $71.47 a share, with 74% coming from shares of Wisconsin Energy, which closed at $46.89 on Friday. The remaining 26% will come from cash.

PARAGRAPH.#text: Utility and energy companies stood out in the flurry of post-Labor Day investment-grade bond issues. Issuance among these companies had declined of late, and the resurgence suggests both the appetite for high-grade bonds among investors and a sense that the time is right to issue this type of debt.

Headlines.Author: Kellie Geressy-Nilsen
Headlines.Headline: Companies Line Up To Sell High-Grade Long-Term Bonds

PARAGRAPH.#text: --Companies are lining up to borrow at discount rates --Buyers willing to lend, eager to put money to work --Emphasis on longer-dated debt, locking in low rates (Updates throughout with prices, additional comment.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Companies swarmed the investment-grade bond market with nearly $13 billion of debt offerings Wednesday, fostered by an improved market tone and urgent investor demand. Nine of 16 issues on offer will mature in 10 or 30 years, underscoring how eager companies are to lock in low rates for the long haul.

Headlines.Headline: Long-Term Borrowers Line Up To Sell High-Grade Corporate Bonds

PARAGRAPH.#text: --Companies are lining up to borrow at discount rates --Buyers willing to lend, eager to put money to work --Emphasis on longer-dated debt, locking in low rates NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Companies swarmed the investment-grade bond market with billions of dollars of debt offerings Wednesday, fostered by an improved market tone and urgent investor demand. Nine of 16 issues on offer will mature in 10 or 30 years, underscoring how eager companies are to lock in low rates for the long haul. Leading the list of issuers are Time Warner Cable Inc.

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: S&P Upgrades Wisconsin Energy On Plant Addition Progress

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Standard & Poor's Ratings Services raised its rating on Wisconsin Energy Corp. WEC, touting the utility company's steps toward completing major generating plant additions and steady progress on environmental compliance. The ratings agency had first hinted toward a possible upgrade on the company in March, when it raised its outlook to positive. The rating was lifted by one notch to A-, which is four levels into investment-grade territory, while the outlook is now stable. Although the company plans to implement up to $300 million in a share repurchase program through 2013 and gradually increase its dividend payout to 60% of earnings, from about 41% last year, beginning in 2012, S&P said it is doing so with an estimated $600 million of free cash flow it expects to have through 2015.
